{{For|the son of Jacob|Gad (son of Jacob)}} '''Gad''' ({{IPAc-en|ɡ|æ|d}}) was a seer or [[prophet]] mentioned in the [[Hebrew Bible]] and the writings of Jewish historian [[Josephus]]. He was one of the personal prophets of [[King David]] of [[Israel]] and, according to the [[Talmud]]ic tradition, some of his writings are believed to be included in the [[Books of Samuel]].<ref>Apologetics Press, [http://www.apologeticspress.org/articles/1972 The Canon and Extra-Canonical Writings], 2003</ref> He is first mentioned in {{bibleverse|1|Samuel|22:5|HE}} telling David to return from refuge in [[Moab]] to the forest of [[Hereth]] in the [[land of Judah]].
The next biblical reference to Gad is {{bibleverse|2|Samuel|24:11-13|HE}} where, after David [[Confession of sin|confesses his sin]] of taking a census of the people of Israel and Judah, God sends Gad to David to offer him a choice of three forms of punishment.<ref>See also Josephus, [http://www.sacred-texts.com/jud/josephus/ant-7.htm ''Antiquities''], 7:13,4</ref>
Gad is mentioned a final time in the [[Books of Samuel]] in {{bibleverse|2|Samuel|24:18|HE}}, coming to David and telling him to build an altar to God after God stops the plague that David had chosen as punishment. The place indicated by Gad for the altar is "in the [[threshing-floor]] of [[Araunah]] the [[Jebusite]]".
{{bibleverse|1|Chronicles|21:18|HE}} tells of an encounter Gad had with the [[angel of the Lord]].
A tomb attributed to Gad is located at [[Halhul]].<ref>''Burial Places of the Fathers'', published by Yehuda Levi Nahum in book: ''Ṣohar la-ḥasifat ginzei teiman'' (Heb. '''צהר לחשיפת גנזי תימן'''), Tel-Aviv 1986, p. 253 (Hebrew)</ref>
==The Chronicles of Gad the seer== {{main|Book of Gad the Seer}}
The words, or chronicle, of Gad the seer are mentioned in {{bibleverse|1|Chronicles|29:29|HE}} and are generally considered a [[Lost books of the Hebrew Bible|lost text]].
