{{Infobox CanadianMP | honorific-prefix =[[The Honourable]] | name = Ginette Petitpas Taylor | honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|MP|size=100%}} | image = Ginette Petitpas Taylor.jpg | imagesize = 200px | office = [[Minister of Health (Canada)|Minister of Health]] | term_start = August 28, 2017 | term_end = | predecessor = [[Jane Philpott]] | primeminister = [[Justin Trudeau]] | office1 = [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]] | minister1 = [[Bill Morneau]] | term_start1 = January 30, 2017 | term_end1 = August 28, 2017 | predecessor1 = [[François-Philippe Champagne]] | successor1 = [[Joël Lightbound]] | office2 = [[Party Whip (Canada)|Deputy Government Whip]] | primeminister2 = [[Justin Trudeau]] | term_start2 = November 20, 2015 | term_end2 = January 29, 2017 | predecessor2 = [[Dave MacKenzie (politician)|Dave MacKenzie]] | successor2 = [[Filomena Tassi]] | riding3 = [[Moncton—Riverview—Dieppe]] | parliament3 = Canadian | term_start3 = October 19, 2015 | term_end3 = | predecessor3 = [[Robert Goguen]] | successor3 = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | profession = | alma_mater = [[Université de Moncton]] | party = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] | residence = | footnotes = | spouse = | children= |}}
'''Marie Ginette Petitpas Taylor''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|MP}} is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician who was elected to represent the [[electoral district (Canada)|riding]] of [[Moncton—Riverview—Dieppe]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] in the [[Canadian federal election, 2015|2015 federal election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/moncton-liberal-ginette-petitpas-taylor-1.3278867|title=Moncton-Riverview-Dieppe turns to Liberal Ginette Petitpas Taylor|date=19 October 2015|work=cbc.ca|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/george-leblanc-loses-bid-for-moncton-liberal-nomination-1.3014514|title=George LeBlanc loses bid for Moncton Liberal nomination|date=30 March 2015|work=cbc.ca|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Liberal Party of Canada]].
Petitpas Taylor grew up in [[Dieppe, New Brunswick|Dieppe]] and graduated from the [[Université de Moncton]] with a bachelor's degree in social work. From 2004 to 2008, she was the chairwoman of the [[New Brunswick]] Advisory Council on the Status of Women, and has held a variety of other jobs aimed at advancing and protecting women's rights, notably as the coordinator for the Victim's Services Program of the local detachment of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]].<ref>[http://ginettepetitpastaylor.liberal.ca/biography/ Meet Ginette Petitpas Taylor], Liberal.ca.</ref> She won the Liberal Party's nomination for [[Moncton—Riverview—Dieppe]] on March 28, 2015, and won the riding itself in the election held on October 19, 2015.<ref>[http://www.919thebend.ca/news/1702808718/ginette-petitpas-taylor-wins-liberal-nomination-moncton-riverview-dieppe Ginette Petitpas Taylor Wins Liberal Nomination For Moncton-Riverview-Dieppe], 919: The Bend, March 29, 2015.</ref>
On December 2, 2015, Prime Minister Justin Trudeau announced the appointment of Petitpas Taylor as deputy government [[Whip (politics)|whip]]. On February 15, 2016, Petitpas Taylor was sworn in as a Member of the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]] according to her duties as Deputy Government Whip.<ref>http://ginglelive.com/share.php?id=10490&thumb=342</ref> She then succeeded [[Jane Philpott]] as [[Minister of Health (Canada)|Minister of Health]] in a cabinet shuffle on August 28, 2017.<ref>https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2017/08/28/seamus-oregan-to-be-named-veterans-minister-as-trudeau-shuffles-cabinet.html</ref><ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/federal-trudeau-cabinet-shuffle-bios-photos-who-1.4265394</ref>
