'''Mikhled Al-Azmi''' is a member of the [[National Assembly of Kuwait|Kuwaiti National Assembly]], representing the [[Kuwait's First District|first district]]. While political parties are technically illegal in Kuwait, Al-Azmi affiliates with Islamist deputies.
==Supports Sharia draft bill== On July 10, 2001, Al-Azmi and [[Waleed Al-Tabtabaie]] presented a draft bill to amend Kuwait's penal code to meet Islamic sharia law.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wwrn.org/article.php?idd=7442&sec=36&con=32 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20071024190515/http://www.wwrn.org/article.php?idd=7442&sec=36&con=32 |archivedate=2007-10-24 |df= }}</ref>
==Protested Against Israeli Attacks== On December 28, 2008, Kuwaiti lawmakers Mikhled Al-Azmi, [[Musallam Al-Barrak]], [[Marzouq Al-Ghanim]], [[Jaaman Al-Harbash]], [[Ahmad Al-Mulaifi]], [[Mohammad Hayef Al-Mutairi]], [[Ahmad Al-Saadoun]], [[Nasser Al-Sane]], and [[Waleed Al-Tabtabaie]] protested in front of the National Assembly building against the attacks by [[Israel]] on [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]]. Protesters burned Israeli flags, waved banners reading, "No to hunger, no to submission" and chanted "Allahu Akbar". Israel launched air strikes against [[Hamas]] in the Gaza Strip on December 26 after a six-month ceasefire ended on December 18.<ref>[http://www.unnindia.com/english/story.php?Id=3746]</ref>
